<h2><a name= "b6"></a>Firewall</h2>
<pre>
<CENTER><h2 style="text-align:center;">What is Firewall?</h2></CENTER>

Firewalls are one of the core components of a network security implementation. Several vendors market firewall solutions
catering to all levels of the marketplace: from home users protecting one PC to data center solutions safeguarding 
vital enterprise information. Firewalls can be standalone hardware solutions, such as firewall appliances by Cisco, Nokia,
and Sonicwall. There are also proprietary software firewall solutions developed for home and business markets by vendors 
such as Checkpoint, McAfee, and Symantec. Apart from the differences between hardware and software firewalls, 
there are also differences in the way firewalls function that separate one solution from another.
<CENTER><h2 style="text-align:center;">How to use firewall </h2></CENTER>

firewall-cmd --get-default-zone                          -query the current default zone
firewall-cmd --set-default-zone=zonename                 -set the defualt zone
firewall-cmd --get-zones                                 -list all avalable zones
firewall-cmd --get-services                              -list all predefined services
firewall-cmd --get-active-zones                          -list all zones currently in use an interface
firewall-cmd --add-source=CIDR --zone=zonename           -route all trafic coming from ip addr or network to specified zone
firewall-cmd --remove-source=CIDR --zone=zonename        -remove the rule rauting all trafic coming from the network/netmask 
                                                          or ip address to specified zone
firewall-cmd --add-interface=intfname --zone=zonename     -route all trafic comming from interface to specified zone
firewall-cmd --change-intface=infname --zone=zonename     -associate the interface with zonename insted of its corrent zone
firewall-cmd --list-all --zone=zonename                   -list all configured interfaces, sources, services and ports 
firewall-cmd --list-all-zones                             -retrieve all information for all zones
firewall-cmd --list-all-ports                             -retrieve all information for all ports
firewall-cmd --add-service=servicename                    -allow trafic to service
firewall-cmd --add-port=portnu/protocol                   -allow trafic to the port number or protocol
firewall-cmd --remove-service=servicename                 -remove service frome the allowed list for zone
firewall-cmd --remove-port=portnu/protocol                -remove the ports frome the allowed list for zone
firewall-cmd --reload                                     -drop the runtime configuration and apply the configuration
firewall-cmd --add-rich-rule='rule'                       -add rule to specified zone
firewall-cmd --remove-rich-rule='rule'                    -remove rule to specified zone
firewall-cmd --query-rich-rule='rule'                     -query rule has been added to the specified zone
firewall-cmd --list-rich-rule='rule'                      -outputs all rich rules for the specified zone

<CENTER><h2 style="text-align:center;">How to add services in firewall  </h2></CENTER>

